Given a number n, check whether it is even or odd. Return true for even and false for odd.

Examples: 
Input: n = 15
Output: false
Explanation: 15 % 2 = 1, so 15 is odd .

Input: n = 44
Output: true
Explanation: 44 % 2 = 0, so 44 is even.

Naive Approach:
Checking for the remainder when divided by 2. 
If the remainder is 0, the number is even, otherwise it is odd. 

For example, when we divide 13 by 2, we get remainder as 1 and when we divide 14 by 2, we get remainder as 0.

Time Complexity: O(1)
Space Complexity: O(1)

Solution:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
     Scanner scn=new Scanner(System.in);
     int n=scn.nextInt();
     if(isEven(n)){
      System.out.println("True");
     }else{
      System.out.println("False");
     }
    }
    public static boolean isEven(int n){
      if(n%2 == 0){
        return true;
      }
      return false;
    }
}

Alternate Approach: Using Bitwise AND operator

The last bit of all odd numbers is always 1, while for even numbers it’s 0. So,
when performing bitwise AND operation with 1, odd numbers give 1, and even numbers give 0.
Note: Bitwise operators are extremely fast and efficient because they operate directly at the binary level,
making them significantly faster than arithmetic or logical operations.

Solution:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
     Scanner scn=new Scanner(System.in);
